04133nmm a2200601Ia 9781438462653DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814384626537 a10.1515/97814384626532doi  a(DE-B1597)683894  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aJN96.A56bC664 2016eb 7aPOL0090002bisacsh04a364.1/32309472231 aNicolescu-Waggonner, Cristina, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNo Rule of Law, No Democracy :bConflicts of Interest, Corruption, and Elections as Democratic Deficits /cCristina Nicolescu-Waggonner. 1aAlbany : bSUNY Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (314 p.) :bTotal Illustrations: 32  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMainstream theories assert that democracy cures corruption. In market economies, however, elections are expensive and parties, with ever-thinning memberships, cannot legally acquire the necessary campaign funds. In order to secure electoral funds, a large number of politicians misappropriate public funds. Due to the illicit character of these transactions, high officials with conflicts of interest prefer to leave anticorruption enforcement mechanisms unreformed and reserve the right to intervene in the judicial process, with dire consequences for the rule of law. In No Rule of Law, No Democracy, Cristina Nicolescu-Waggonner demonstrates that when corrupt politicians are in power—true of nearly all new democracies—they will protect their office and fail to implement rule of law reforms. Consequently, these polities never reach a point where democracy could and would cure corruption. This dysfunction is tested in one hundred cases over sixteen years with significant results. In the case of the Czech Republic, for example, which is regarded as a consolidated democracy, there is systematic corruption, misappropriation of state funds, an unreformed judiciary, and arbitrary application of law. The only solution is a powerful, independent, well-funded anticorruption agency. Romania, one of the most corrupt countries in Europe, established, at the European Union's request, powerful anticorruption bodies and punished corrupt leaders, which created the predictability of enforcement. It is the certainty of punishment that curtails corruption and establishes true rule of law.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aConflict of interestsxPolitical aspectsxEurope, Eastern. 0aConflict of interestsxPolitical aspectszEurope, Eastern. 0aNew democraciesxEurope, Eastern. 0aNew democracieszEurope, Eastern. 0aPolitical campaignsxCorrupt practicesxEurope, Eastern. 0aPolitical campaignsxCorrupt practiceszEurope, Eastern. 0aPolitical corruptionxEurope, Eastern. 0aPolitical corruptionzEurope, Eastern. 0aRule of lawxEurope, Eastern. 0aRule of lawzEurope, Eastern. 4aCriminology : Criminology. 4aPolitics and Law : Comparative Politics. 4aPolitics and Law : Democratization. 4aPolitics and Law : Leadership Studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143846265340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438462653423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438462653/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles